---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import SiteHeader from "../components/SiteHeader.astro";

const tutorials = (await getCollection("tutorials")).sort((a, b) => a.data.order - b.data.order);
const explanations = (await getCollection("explanations")).sort((a, b) => a.data.order - b.data.order);
const tutorialHref = (slug: string) => `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}tutorials/${slug}/`;
const explanationHref = (slug: string) => `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}explanations/${slug}/`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Linkar | Reusable Analysis Resources For Humans And Machines"
  description="Linkar helps teams turn scripts, CLI tools, notebooks, and analysis steps into reusable templates and bindings, with a short CLI for humans and a local API for machines."
>
  <div class="page-shell">
    <SiteHeader />

    <main>
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">The Problem</p>
          <h2>Real analysis work needs both customization and reuse.</h2>
          <p class="section-copy">
            Data scientists often start from something useful already: a script, a package, a CLI
            tool, or a notebook. Then reality arrives. Inputs differ, defaults change, one step
            must feed another, and the same local adjustments get repeated by hand. That is where
            reuse becomes fragile and chaining becomes error-prone.
          </p>
          <p class="section-copy">
            The name reflects that goal: Linkar stands for <code>LINKing All Resources</code>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card-grid three-up">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Useful resources drift into one-off work</h3>
            <p>
              Scripts and notebooks are easy to adapt once, but hard to reuse cleanly when params,
              outputs, and environment assumptions stay implicit.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Generalization can kill practicality</h3>
            <p>
              Many systems become too abstract too early. You need a reusable step, not a whole new
              workflow language just to keep a tool portable.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Manual chaining creates avoidable mistakes</h3>
            <p>
              When one analysis feeds another, retyping paths and choices again and again is slow,
              inconsistent, and easy to get wrong.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section section-dark">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">The Model</p>
          <h2>Linkar packages reusable work and the logic that connects it.</h2>
          <p class="section-copy">
            Linkar is the core runtime. Packs are where users capture reusable capabilities. A pack
            combines standalone templates with bindings that define how steps connect and where
            custom logic should live.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card-grid three-up">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Templates are standalone units</h3>
            <p>
              A template defines explicit input params and output params. It can include scripts,
              helper files, environment config, and tests, but it should still be runnable and
              testable on its own.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Bindings capture reusable customization</h3>
            <p>
              Bindings define how outputs from one template become inputs to another. They also
              hold custom functions so repeated mapping or transformation only needs to be defined
              once.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Packs are personal or shared assets</h3>
            <p>
              A pack is the reusable surface area of your work: templates plus pack-level bindings.
              Projects stay local and readable while packs stay portable between users and teams.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section section-alt">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Interfaces</p>
          <h2>One runtime for human use and machine automation.</h2>
          <p class="section-copy">
            Linkar is the same core software either way. Humans use a short CLI. Machines use the
            same semantics through the local API or MCP tools. Both paths write the same readable
            run artifact on disk.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="interface-grid">
          <article class="interface-card">
            <div class="interface-head">
              <span class="interface-tag">Human</span>
              <h3>Short CLI for daily analysis work</h3>
            </div>
            <p>
              Discover the current project, expose template params as flags, and keep the path
              short enough that people will actually use it.
            </p>
            <pre><code>linkar config author set --name "Your Name"
linkar project init --name study
cd study
linkar pack add ~/github/izkf_genomics_pack --id izkf
linkar run fastqc --input sample.fastq.gz
linkar inspect run fastqc_001</code></pre>
          </article>

          <article class="interface-card">
            <div class="interface-head">
              <span class="interface-tag">Machine</span>
              <h3>Local API and MCP for structured automation</h3>
            </div>
            <p>
              Agents and tools can inspect templates, resolve params, run work, and consume
              outputs without scraping shell text or inventing their own state model.
            </p>
            <pre><code>linkar serve --port 8000

GET  /templates
POST /resolve
POST /run
GET  /runs/&lcub;run_ref&rcub;/outputs
GET  /runs/&lcub;run_ref&rcub;/runtime

linkar mcp serve</code></pre>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Learn In Order</p>
          <h2>Start with the model, then follow the path that matches your job.</h2>
          <p class="section-copy">
            The site is organized around three questions: what Linkar is, how to use it, and what
            the contracts are. Start with concepts if you are new, then move into tutorials or the
            reference depending on whether you are running packs, authoring them, or automating them.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="split-grid">
          <article class="content-card">
            <h3>1. Understand the concept</h3>
            <p>
              Start with the explanation pages to learn the product identity, the role of packs and
              projects, and why templates and bindings are separate.
            </p>
            <div class="hero-actions">
              <a class="button button-secondary" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}explanations/`}>Browse concepts</a>
            </div>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <h3>2. Follow a tutorial path</h3>
            <p>
              Use the tutorials to set up a project, run a pack, author templates, test them, and
              expose Linkar to agents or other automation.
            </p>
            <div class="hero-actions">
              <a class="button button-secondary" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}tutorials/`}>Browse tutorials</a>
            </div>
          </article>
        </div>

        <div class="card-grid two-up section-top-gap">
          {explanations.slice(0, 2).map((entry) => (
            <a class="doc-card" href={explanationHref(entry.slug)}>
              <h3>{entry.data.title}</h3>
              <p>{entry.data.description}</p>
            </a>
          ))}
          {tutorials.slice(0, 2).map((entry) => (
            <a class="tutorial-card tutorial-link" href={tutorialHref(entry.slug)}>
              <h3>{entry.data.title}</h3>
              <p>{entry.data.description}</p>
              <span class="status-tag">{entry.data.status}</span>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>

        <div class="hero-actions section-top-gap">
          <a class="button button-primary" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}tutorials/getting-started/`}>Start with getting started</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}reference/`}>Open reference</a>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
